x4freetext: Experiment performed at LANSCE
accelerator, which delivered 800 MeV protons to the
unmoderated tungsten target at WNR using 90 deg flight
path.
Active volumen of diamond detector was used as active
target.
Cividec B8 sCVD diamond detector was used to detect
charged particle products. Detector dimensions
were 4 x 4 mm2 and thickness 500 mu-m. Detector was
placed at a distance of 7.618 m from the spallation
target.
Time of flight was used to determine neutron
energy. The time structure of the LANSCE proton beam
consisted of 40 macropulses/second. Each micropulse
was 625 mu-s long and consisted of 340 micropulses,
separated by 1.8 mu-s. Width of each micropulse was
approx. 1 ns.
Data normalized to recent EXFOR data around 14.1 MeV
Spallation reaction of 800 MeV protons on
tungsten target and 90L beamline was used to produce
neutrons. No moderator was used. Neutrons were
collimated using primary and secondary collimators
with inner diameter of 6 mm.
The relative flux normalization was obtained from
measurements of the 238U(n,f) and 235U(n,f) cross
section.
Overall normalization was made by normalizing the
measured yield for the 12C(n,a) reaction at 14.1
MeV to the weighted average of experimental data
from EXFOR database
Uncertainty caused by relative shape of
neutron flux
